Textbook 3.7.1

P.1

stat_summary() provides geom_pointrange() as its default. The default geom function could be customized by the geom argument. The above plot also can be created by the code below, using geom_pointrange().

ggplot(data=diamonds, mapping=aes(x=cut, y=depth)) + 
  geom_pointrange(
    stat="summary",
    fun.ymin=min,
    fun.ymax=max,
    fun.y=median
    )

P.5

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = ..prop..))

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = color, y = ..prop..))

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = ..prop.., group="something"))

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = ..count../sum(..count..), fill = color))

The default group option is by the x-axis variable of the graph, in this case, cut. That is, geom_bar() in default shows the count of the data grouped by x-axis variable, cut.

When y-axis is set to be proportion, however, as the data is grouped by cut, each groups proportion shoud be 1. That is, the proportion of the Fair in Fair group should be 1, which is happening in the first graph. In order to show the proportion, we should set group=something so that the default group setting is overrided and the proportion is calculated in total.

Reference: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/39878813/ggplot-geom-bar-meaning-of-aesgroup-1

Or we can fill the graph with proportional y-axis by just normalizing the y-axis.

Textbook 3.8.1

P.1

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(position="jitter")

The data seem to be rounded that the points overlap each other. With this overplotting problem, we cannot clearly see the distribution of the data. This problem can be handled by jitter for position argument, which adds a random noise for each data point.

P.3

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_jitter()

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_count()

geom_count() shows the number of overplotted points by its size, whereas geom_jitter() deals with overplotting problem by adding random noises to each point. geom_count() would be adequate for discrete variables such as age, counts, and so on. On the other hand, geom_jitter() would be adequate for successive variables such as temperature, weight, and so on when overplotting problem is present by rounding.

bar_chart

bar_chart + coord_polar(theta = "y")

P.4

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_abline() +
  coord_fixed()

A fixed scale coordinate system forces the ratio of the length of a unit for y-axis to the length of a unit for x-axis. The default ratio is 1, which means a unit length of both axes are same. Otherwise, the map would be distorted. geom_abline() provides a reference line (horizontal, vertical or diagonal) for the current coordinate system.
